Note:
HASHMAP - Open-Addressing Linear-Probing Hash Map Tier 0 Primitive

This file implements a HashMap distinct from compiler/.../dictionary.runa.
Where Dictionary uses chained hashing (one linked list per bucket),
HashMap uses open addressing with linear probing: every entry lives
directly in the bucket array, displaced linearly forward on collision.

Open addressing wins on cache locality (a hot probe stays in the same
cache line as the bucket) at the cost of more careful tombstone
handling for delete.

Entry layout (24 bytes):
  offset 0:  state (8 bytes; 0 = EMPTY, 1 = OCCUPIED, 2 = TOMBSTONE)
  offset 8:  key (8 bytes; integer-or-pointer)
  offset 16: value (8 bytes)

HashMap header (40 bytes):
  offset 0:  entries (pointer to bucket array)
  offset 8:  capacity (power of two)
  offset 16: count (occupied entries)
  offset 24: tombstones (count of TOMBSTONE entries)
  offset 32: hash_seed (for hash mixing)
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Let HASHMAP_HEADER_SIZE be 40
Let HASHMAP_ENTRY_SIZE be 24
Let HASHMAP_INITIAL_CAPACITY be 16
Let HASHMAP_STATE_EMPTY be 0
Let HASHMAP_STATE_OCCUPIED be 1
Let HASHMAP_STATE_TOMBSTONE be 2
Let HASHMAP_LOAD_NUMERATOR be 75
Let HASHMAP_LOAD_DENOMINATOR be 100

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HASH HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Mix an integer key into a well-distributed bucket index. Uses a
splitmix64-style multiplicative mix, then masks to the capacity mask.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
h = key XOR (key >> 33);
h = h * 0xff51afd7ed558ccd;
h = h XOR (h >> 33);
h = h * 0xc4ceb9fe1a85ec53;
h = h XOR (h >> 33);
return h AND (capacity - 1).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Non-cryptographic mix.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "hashmap_index" takes key as Integer, capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    Let h be key
    Set h to h bitwise xor (h shifted right by 33)
    Set h to h multiplied by 18397679294719823053
    Set h to h bitwise xor (h shifted right by 33)
    Set h to h multiplied by 14181476777654086739
    Set h to h bitwise xor (h shifted right by 33)
    Let mask be capacity minus 1
    Return h bitwise and mask
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ENTRY ADDRESS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Address of entry slot at index i.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
addr = entries + i * 24.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-validated index.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "hashmap_entry_addr" takes entries as Integer, i as Integer returns Integer:
    Return entries plus (i multiplied by HASHMAP_ENTRY_SIZE)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTRUCTION / DESTRUCTION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Create an empty HashMap with INITIAL_CAPACITY buckets.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocate header and entries; zero-init entries so every state field is
EMPTY. Initialize header fields.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(capacity * 24 / 8) bytes zero-init.
Space: 40 + 24 * capacity = 40 + 384 bytes initial.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "hashmap_create" returns Integer:
    Let hm be proc allocate from Layout with HASHMAP_HEADER_SIZE
    If hm is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let entries_bytes be HASHMAP_INITIAL_CAPACITY multiplied by HASHMAP_ENTRY_SIZE
    Let entries be proc allocate from Layout with entries_bytes
    If entries is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with hm
        Return 0
    End If
    Let zi be 0
    While zi is less than entries_bytes:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with entries, zi, 0
        Set zi to zi plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with hm, 0, entries
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with hm, 8, HASHMAP_INITIAL_CAPACITY
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with hm, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with hm, 24, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with hm, 32, 2654435761
    Return hm
End Process

@Reasoning
Destroy a HashMap.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Free entries then header.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-owned.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "hashmap_destroy" takes hm as Integer returns Integer:
    If hm is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let entries be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 0
    If entries is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with entries
    End If
    proc deallocate from Layout with hm
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PROBE / FIND
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Probe the table starting at the hashed slot, walking linearly forward.
Returns the slot index where the key was found, or the first EMPTY
slot encountered if absent. TOMBSTONE entries are skipped during probe
but recorded as candidate insertion slots.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) idx = hash(key) bitwise and (cap - 1).
2) Loop: read state at idx. If EMPTY, return idx (or first_tombstone if
   seen). If OCCUPIED and key match, return idx. Otherwise advance:
   idx = (idx + 1) and mask.
3) On full table this would loop forever, but the resize keeps load
   below 0.75 so the loop terminates.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1) amortized.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Internal helper.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "hashmap_probe" takes hm as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    Let entries be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 0
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 8
    Let mask be capacity minus 1
    Let idx be proc hashmap_index with key, capacity
    Let first_tombstone be 0 minus 1
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let addr be proc hashmap_entry_addr with entries, idx
        Let state be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
        If state is equal to HASHMAP_STATE_EMPTY:
            If first_tombstone is not equal to 0 minus 1:
                Return first_tombstone
            End If
            Return idx
        End If
        If state is equal to HASHMAP_STATE_OCCUPIED:
            Let k be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 8
            If k is equal to key:
                Return idx
            End If
        End If
        If state is equal to HASHMAP_STATE_TOMBSTONE:
            If first_tombstone is equal to 0 minus 1:
                Set first_tombstone to idx
            End If
        End If
        Set idx to (idx plus 1) bitwise and mask
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: RESIZE
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Grow capacity by 2x and re-probe all live entries. Resize triggers
when (count + tombstones) >= capacity * 3 / 4.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Allocate new bucket array of double capacity, zero-init.
2) Walk old buckets; for each OCCUPIED entry, recompute slot in the
   new array and write.
3) Free old array, install new pointer, update fields.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n + capacity). Space: O(2 * old capacity).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure; existing table unchanged.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "hashmap_resize" takes hm as Integer returns Integer:
    Let old_entries be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 0
    Let old_capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 8
    Let new_capacity be old_capacity multiplied by 2
    Let new_bytes be new_capacity multiplied by HASHMAP_ENTRY_SIZE
    Let new_entries be proc allocate from Layout with new_bytes
    If new_entries is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let zi be 0
    While zi is less than new_bytes:
        proc memory_set_byte from Memory with new_entries, zi, 0
        Set zi to zi plus 1
    End While
    Let new_mask be new_capacity minus 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than old_capacity:
        Let addr be proc hashmap_entry_addr with old_entries, i
        Let state be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
        If state is equal to HASHMAP_STATE_OCCUPIED:
            Let k be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 8
            Let v be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 16
            Let new_idx be proc hashmap_index with k, new_capacity
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let new_addr be proc hashmap_entry_addr with new_entries, new_idx
                Let new_state be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with new_addr, 0
                If new_state is equal to HASHMAP_STATE_EMPTY:
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_addr, 0, HASHMAP_STATE_OCCUPIED
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_addr, 8, k
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_addr, 16, v
                    Set new_idx to new_capacity
                End If
                If new_idx is greater than or equal to new_capacity:
                    Set new_idx to 0
                Otherwise:
                    Set new_idx to (new_idx plus 1) bitwise and new_mask
                End If
            End While
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc deallocate from Layout with old_entries
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with hm, 0, new_entries
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with hm, 8, new_capacity
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with hm, 24, 0
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PUBLIC API
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Insert or update a key/value pair.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) If (count + tombstones) * LOAD_DENOMINATOR >= capacity * LOAD_NUMERATOR,
   resize first.
2) Probe for the key.
3) If the slot's state is OCCUPIED and key matches, overwrite value.
4) Else write OCCUPIED + key + value, increment count.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: amortized O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure during resize.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "hashmap_set" takes hm as Integer, key as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    If hm is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 16
    Let tombs be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 24
    Let cap be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 8
    Let occupancy be count plus tombs
    Let threshold be (cap multiplied by HASHMAP_LOAD_NUMERATOR) divided by HASHMAP_LOAD_DENOMINATOR
    If occupancy is greater than or equal to threshold:
        Let r be proc hashmap_resize with hm
        If r is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    Let idx be proc hashmap_probe with hm, key
    Let entries be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 0
    Let addr be proc hashmap_entry_addr with entries, idx
    Let state be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
    If state is equal to HASHMAP_STATE_OCCUPIED:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with addr, 16, value
        Return 1
    End If
    If state is equal to HASHMAP_STATE_TOMBSTONE:
        Let new_tombs be tombs minus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with hm, 24, new_tombs
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with addr, 0, HASHMAP_STATE_OCCUPIED
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with addr, 8, key
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with addr, 16, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with hm, 16, count plus 1
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Lookup value for key.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Probe; if slot is OCCUPIED with matching key, return value; else 0.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1) average.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "hashmap_get" takes hm as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    If hm is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let idx be proc hashmap_probe with hm, key
    Let entries be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 0
    Let addr be proc hashmap_entry_addr with entries, idx
    Let state be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
    If state is not equal to HASHMAP_STATE_OCCUPIED:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let k be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 8
    If k is not equal to key:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 16
End Process

@Reasoning
Containment predicate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Probe; return 1 if found.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1) average.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "hashmap_contains" takes hm as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    If hm is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let idx be proc hashmap_probe with hm, key
    Let entries be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 0
    Let addr be proc hashmap_entry_addr with entries, idx
    Let state be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
    If state is not equal to HASHMAP_STATE_OCCUPIED:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let k be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 8
    If k is equal to key:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Remove key by marking the slot as TOMBSTONE. We do not shift entries
because that would break later probes for keys whose hash chain
includes the removed slot.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Probe for key.
2) If found, mark state = TOMBSTONE, decrement count, increment
   tombstones.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1) average.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 if not present.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "hashmap_remove" takes hm as Integer, key as Integer returns Integer:
    If hm is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let idx be proc hashmap_probe with hm, key
    Let entries be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 0
    Let addr be proc hashmap_entry_addr with entries, idx
    Let state be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
    If state is not equal to HASHMAP_STATE_OCCUPIED:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let k be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 8
    If k is not equal to key:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with addr, 0, HASHMAP_STATE_TOMBSTONE
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with hm, 16, count minus 1
    Let tombs be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 24
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with hm, 24, tombs plus 1
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Element count.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Read count field at offset 16.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "hashmap_size" takes hm as Integer returns Integer:
    If hm is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 16
End Process

@Reasoning
Capacity accessor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Read capacity field at offset 8.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "hashmap_capacity" takes hm as Integer returns Integer:
    If hm is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 8
End Process

@Reasoning
Empty predicate.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 if count == 0.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "hashmap_is_empty" takes hm as Integer returns Integer:
    If hm is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with hm, 16
    If count is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process
